### Defunct political subdivisions

The historical landscape of the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) is littered with the ghosts of once-incorporated localities, entities that, for various reasons, have become legally void. While the notable exception of [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia) was largely abandoned by its citizens, most other defunct subdivisions were absorbed into larger, consolidating entities rather than simply fading into obscurity. Excluding those towns that transitioned into cities while retaining their original names, the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) area alone has seen the disappearance of no fewer than 4 shires, 2 counties, 4 towns, and 1 city, all of which no longer exist under their earlier administrative designations. This relentless administrative evolution reflects a pattern of growth, consolidation, and the shifting tides of human settlement and governance, leaving behind a complex legacy of names and boundaries.

The following is a comprehensive listing of these 11 extinct shires, counties, towns, and cities, accompanied by their approximate periods of existence:

*   [Jamestown, Virginia](/Jamestown,_Virginia) (established 1607) – largely abandoned as a formal Town after 1699, its significance becoming purely historical.
*   [Kecoughtan, Virginia](/Kecoughtan,_Virginia) (established 1610) – eventually became an integral part of the expanding Town and later [City of Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia), its identity subsumed by its larger neighbor.
*   [Middle Plantation](/Middle_Plantation_(Virginia)) (established 1632) – famously renamed [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) after 1699, becoming the colonial capital.
*   [Elizabeth River Shire](/Elizabeth_River_Shire) (1634–1643) – an early administrative division, its boundaries and purpose later redefined.
*   [Warwick River Shire](/Warwick_River_Shire) (1634–1643) – another of the original eight shires, its existence was relatively brief before being reorganized.
*   [Charles River Shire](/Charles_River_Shire) (1634–1643) – a foundational shire, which, like its contemporaries, underwent significant administrative changes.
*   [James City Shire](/James_City_Shire) (1634–1643) – the original designation for the area around [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), later evolving into [James City County](/James_City_County,_Virginia).
*   [Elizabeth City County](/Elizabeth_City_County,_Virginia) (1643–1952) – a long-standing county that, through consolidation, now forms a substantial part of the modern [City of Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia).
*   [Warwick County](/Warwick_County,_Virginia) (also known as Warwick River County) (1643–1952) – a historic county that ultimately merged to become part of the [City of Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia).
*   [Town of Phoebus](/Phoebus,_Virginia) (incorporated 1900–1952) – previously known by the less formal names of Millwood, Roseland Farms, and Chesapeake City, it too was absorbed into the [City of Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia).
*   [City of Warwick](/Warwick,_Virginia) (1952–1958) – a short-lived independent city created from [Warwick County](/Warwick_County,_Virginia), which then rapidly consolidated with [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) to form the larger modern city.

## Major bridges, bridge tunnels, ferry system

Inevitably surrounded by a veritable embrace of water, the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) finds itself inextricably linked to other vital areas across the formidable aquatic barriers of the [James](/James_River) and [York Rivers](/York_River_(Virginia)), as well as the expansive natural harbor of [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads). These crucial connections are maintained through a remarkable network of modern engineering feats: specifically, two intricate [bridge–tunnels](/Bridge%E2%80%93tunnel), two substantial [drawbridges](/Drawbridge), and a perpetually active, state-operated [ferry](/Ferry) system. These vital arteries are not merely conveniences but fundamental components of the region's infrastructure, facilitating commerce, military operations, and daily commutes across what would otherwise be impassable waterways.

These indispensable crossings include:

*   [Hampton Roads Bridge–Tunnel](/Hampton_Roads_Bridge%E2%80%93Tunnel) – A critical link connecting [Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia) on the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) to [Norfolk](/Norfolk,_Virginia) on the Southside, notorious for its traffic during peak hours, a testament to its essential role.
*   [Monitor–Merrimac Memorial Bridge–Tunnel](/Monitor%E2%80%93Merrimac_Memorial_Bridge%E2%80%93Tunnel) – Named in homage to the famous ironclads, this structure provides an alternate, though equally vital, route between [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) and [Suffolk](/Suffolk,_Virginia), easing congestion on its older counterpart.
*   [James River Bridge](/James_River_Bridge) – A lengthy [drawbridge](/Drawbridge) that connects [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) to [Isle of Wight County](/Isle_of_Wight_County,_Virginia), providing a crucial passage over the wide [James River](/James_River).
*   [George P. Coleman Memorial Bridge](/George_P._Coleman_Memorial_Bridge) – This impressive [drawbridge](/Drawbridge) spans the [York River](/York_River_(Virginia)), linking [Yorktown](/Yorktown,_Virginia) on the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) with [Gloucester Point](/Gloucester_Point) on the [Middle Peninsula](/Middle_Peninsula), a vital artery for regional connectivity.
*   [Jamestown Ferry](/Jamestown_Ferry) – A free, state-run ferry service that crosses the [James River](/James_River) near the historic site of [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), offering a scenic and functional alternative to bridges for both residents and tourists.

### Interstate Highways

The [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) is efficiently traversed by a network of [Interstate Highways](/Interstate_Highway_System), which serve as the primary conduits for regional and interstate travel, connecting its vital urban centers and military installations to the wider national grid.

*   [Interstate 64](/Interstate_64_(Virginia)) – The backbone of the region's transportation system, running east-west and connecting the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) to [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) and [Virginia Beach](/Virginia_Beach,_Virginia).
*   [Interstate 664](/Interstate_664_(Virginia)) – A crucial north-south spur that forms the western segment of the [Hampton Roads Beltway](/Hampton_Roads_Beltway), encompassing the [Monitor–Merrimac Memorial Bridge–Tunnel](/Monitor%E2%80%93Merrimac_Memorial_Bridge%E2%80%93Tunnel).
*   [Hampton Roads Beltway](/Hampton_Roads_Beltway) – The overarching circulatory system for the entire [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads) metropolitan area, integrating both [I-64](/Interstate_64_(Virginia)) and [I-664](/Interstate_664_(Virginia)) to facilitate movement around the complex urban landscape.

### U.S. and State Routes

Beyond the Interstate network, a comprehensive system of U.S. and State Routes further crisscrosses the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula), providing essential local and regional access, often predating the superhighways and connecting more intimate communities.

*   [U.S. Route 17](/U.S._Route_17_(Virginia)) – A significant north-south route traversing the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula), connecting various towns and offering an alternative to the Interstate system.
*   [U.S. Route 60](/U.S._Route_60_(Virginia)) – An historic east-west route that traces much of the original colonial road, passing through [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) and [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia).
*   [U.S. Route 258](/U.S._Route_258_(Virginia)) – Providing north-south access, particularly in the western parts of the [Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula).
*   [State Route 5](/State_Route_5_(Virginia)) – A scenic route connecting [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) to [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia), winding through historic plantations along the [James River](/James_River).
*   [State Route 31](/State_Route_31_(Virginia)) – Connecting [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) to the [Jamestown Ferry](/Jamestown_Ferry), a vital tourist and commuter link.
*   [State Route 32](/State_Route_32_(Virginia)) – A less prominent but still functional state route within the region.
*   [State Route 134](/State_Route_134_(Virginia)) – Serving local traffic, particularly in the [Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia) area.
*   [State Route 143](/State_Route_143_(Virginia)) – Paralleling [I-64](/Interstate_64_(Virginia)) for much of its length, offering local access between [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia) and [Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia).
*   [State Route 199](/State_Route_199_(Virginia)) (Humelsine Parkway) – A crucial loop around [Williamsburg](/Williamsburg,_Virginia), facilitating access to [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg) and other attractions while bypassing the historic core.

### Scenic parkways and trails

Beyond mere utilitarian transport, the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula) also offers pathways designed for aesthetic appreciation and recreational pursuits, connecting significant historical sites with deliberate grace.

*   [Colonial Parkway](/Colonial_Parkway) – A meticulously maintained, scenic roadway constructed by the [National Park Service](/National_Park_Service) that seamlessly connects [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), [Colonial Williamsburg](/Colonial_Williamsburg), and [Yorktown](/Yorktown,_Virginia), offering unparalleled views and a deliberate lack of commercial intrusions.
*   [Virginia Capital Trail](/Virginia_Capital_Trail) – A dedicated multi-use trail stretching from [Richmond](/Richmond,_Virginia) to [Jamestown](/Jamestown,_Virginia), providing a picturesque and historically significant route for cyclists and pedestrians, linking the past to the present.

## U.S. military installations

Two F-22A turn in on final approach to [Langley Air Force Base](/Langley_Air_Force_Base)

The [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula), perhaps more than any other region in [Virginia](/Virginia), serves as a critical nexus for the [Military of the United States](/Military_of_the_United_States), hosting an impressive array of strategic installations that underscore its enduring importance to national defense.

### City of Hampton

The [City of Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia) is home to [Langley Air Force Base](/Langley_Air_Force_Base), a foundational installation for air power that has evolved significantly since its inception. It serves as a vital hub for air superiority and reconnaissance, reflecting the ongoing strategic importance of the region. Nearby, [Fort Monroe](/Fort_Monroe) once stood as the oldest continuously garrisoned military post in the nation until its decommissioning in September 2011. While no longer active militarily, its historical significance as a coastal defense bastion and a symbol of Union control during the Civil War remains profound. Across the mouth of [Hampton Roads](/Hampton_Roads), situated on the man-made island known as [Rip Raps](/Rip_Raps), lies the now-decommissioned [Fort Wool](/Fort_Wool), another testament to the region's historical role in coastal defense, also falling under the jurisdiction of [Hampton](/Hampton,_Virginia).

### City of Newport News

[Newport News](/Newport_News,_Virginia) hosts [Fort Eustis](/Fort_Eustis), a sprawling U.S. Army installation that is famously home to the [U.S. Army Training and Doctrine Command (TRADOC)](/U.S._Army_Training_and_Doctrine_Command_(TRADOC)). This base is a powerhouse of military education and logistics, crucial for developing army doctrine and training future leaders. Furthermore, the city is intrinsically linked to the defense industry through the presence of [Newport News Shipbuilding](/Newport_News_Shipbuilding), a major military contractor and the sole designer, builder, and refueler of U.S. Navy aircraft carriers, alongside building submarines, making it a cornerstone of national naval power.

### York County

[York County](/York_County,_Virginia) plays a critical role in naval operations, housing the U.S. Navy's expansive [Yorktown Naval Weapons Station](/Yorktown_Naval_Weapons_Station). This facility is a primary ordnance loading point for the U.S. Atlantic Fleet. Adjacent to it is a significant supply depot at Cheatham Annex, further bolstering logistical capabilities. Also located within [York County](/York_County,_Virginia) are the highly covert [Camp Peary](/Camp_Peary), often speculated to be a CIA training facility, and the [Coast Guard Training Center Yorktown](/USCG_Training_Center_Yorktown), which serves as a vital institution for training Coast Guard personnel.

### James City County

While primarily situated in other jurisdictions, the strategic importance of these military installations means their expansive footprints often bleed across county lines. Consequently, portions of [Fort Eustis](/Fort_Eustis), the [Naval Weapons Station Yorktown](/Naval_Weapons_Station_Yorktown), Cheatham Annex, and the secretive [Camp Peary](/Camp_Peary) all extend into the territory of [James City County](/James_City_County,_Virginia), illustrating the integrated and interconnected nature of military operations within the [Virginia Peninsula](/Virginia_Peninsula).

